<br>
Founders Federation member here.  Got in on the last part of closed Beta and am now on my two week head start before release.  I believe release is first week of October.<br>
<br>
Impressions: Hmm.  So far I like it.  Graphics are good.  Gameplay is good but of course can be laggy.  Space is done in 2D for travel with a limited z axis to make things more interesting in combat.  Wide variety of enemies and missions, at least up to 50th level (max I was able to get because of p-wipes).  You can fight, explore, or trade but need to do some of all of that to progress.  I heard some noise about higher level quests being more rare but not near as much as in DAoC.  Lots of people take up building items as they are much better than vendor items so are in high demand.<br>
<br>
The game can be played in 3rd person or 1st person view with adjustable cameras. Gameplay is like the other mmogs out, ie one character played (five chars per server) , level progression, kill, loot, trade, explore, loot more, kill more, etc.<br>
<br>
Six combinations of race/class.  Warriors, Traders, Explorers.  Balance between the classes seems to be pretty good.  Straight line skill progression with each race/class type getting different mixtures of skills that help out in weak areas, ie the Jenquai Defender(warrior) is light on Hull/Shields. For skills they get Cloak, Psionic Shield, and Fold Space to make up for the weak areas.  Their best weaponry are Beams, which are the shortest range weapon in the game, so they get Summon Skill which allows them to summon enemies (and friends) to them.  <br>
<br>
Each race can also build items. Weapons, Engines, Shields, Reactors, Devices and ammo. Each races has something they make best and some things are restricted from use by other races.  Item usage is limited by skill level so there is no &quot;twinking&quot;. Parts to build items are bought, looted and minerals for certain things (ammo components I think) are prospected (mined from asteroids).<br>
<br>
The Races are: <br>
Progen - Genetically engineered Warrior Humans. Their classes are the Warrior and the Sentinal (warrior/explorer).<br>
Terrans - Your average human, the best traders in the game. Classes are Trader and Enforcer(trader/warrior)<br>
Jenquai - A more mystically inclined Human.  Classes are Explorer and Defender (warrior/explorer)<br>
<br>
Levels go from 1 to 150 with three types of levels that cap at 50 each.  Level types are: Combat, Exploration, Trade.  You gain xp in each type depending on what you do.  Skills can be total level dependent or depend on a specific type of level (ie, Beam skill is determined by Combat Level). Skills are progressed by points awarded for leveling.  Each skill gets progressively better as you advance it.<br>
<br>
At certain levels you gain a new title, your ship's hull is upgraded (stronger hull, more slots for weapons/devices), and you go on a mission (with many sub-missions) which you have to complete to actually gain your new title.  The Jenquai Defender I took to 50th level completed her 30th level Title mission at 46th level. I thought I was doing it slow at first but then reached a point in the mission where I was required to be 45th level to gain a skill I needed to do the sub-mission. I was 46th at the time so I considered the entire mission to be well designed.  During this time I did normal fighting, some trading, lots of exploring and several other missions (some generated by &quot;stations&quot; which give out random Explore/Combat/Trade missions). All in all I never got bored.<br>
<br>
Each class brings to a group some bonus, whether it be to targeting, shields, etc.  There is a grouping xp bonus. <br>
There are formations and assisting to help in grouping.<br>
<br>
There is a fairly good guild system in place but I haven't looked at it much.<br>
<br>
There will be PvP in some outlying sectors, but they are not enabling it for Beta (ie, no testing by the average player, look for incoming nerfs to balance out the classes against each other).<br>
<br>
Dying...  When your ship is &quot;destroyed&quot; it's actually disabled. You can opt for a tow back to the last station you visited (ie, &quot;Gate to Bind&quot; hehe) which will incure a repair cost, sit there and admire space, or turn on a distress beacon (sit there and admire space but people know you're disabled).  Some classes get the Jumpstart skilll. This is essentially a ress.  Dying results in an xp debt.  You never loose xp, and when you have an xp debt, half your gained xp will go to pay off that debt until it's gone. The rest goes to normal xp. Jumpstarts will reduce that debt (ie, % ress) by a certain amount depending on the Jumpstarter's skill.<br>
Some players bitch about the debt at high levels, but former EQ players tell them to try out EQ then come back and complain. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  There are no corpse retrievals, no lost items, etc. Only xp debt and repair cost if you opt for the tow.   <br>
<br>
Ok, that's it in a nutshell.  Will I be playing it?  Yes for a while. I'll give it the same chance I gave DAoC and AO (the second time around). <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/udorraxx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dorraxx</A> at: 9/16/02 6:12:10 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/utaldaryefairglade.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Taldarye Fairglade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Not mean, cute!</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/17/02 12:53:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub141.ezboard.com/fthemithrilheartbrigade7573generaldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3041.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Earth and Beyond</span><hr size=1> I was somewhat impressed by it.   I won't be playing it anymore until I get my new computer though. <p><html>

